metadata.name: WRAPPERS #55
metadata.description:
Generative animated artwork made using shader feedback and pixel quantization.

WRAPPERS is a study of virtual surfaces and textures. It explores the tension between hard and soft forms and parallel projection, where the illusion of perspective is flattened into a highly geometric composition. These geometries feature a flowing texture that runs infinitely, reflecting on the endless nature of virtual space. The project blends together imagery from early computer terminals, video games, and ascii art to produce a dynamic, intricate, visual experience.

WRAPPERS is very GPU intensive. For a smoother experience, you can change the scale by adding the parameter "?scale=2" to the URL.

Press 'i' to invert the colors.
Press '1', '2', '3', '4', '5', '6' to scale the bitmap glyphs.
Press 'g' to download a looping animated GIF (150 frames). Please make sure to let the animation run for at least 30 seconds first.
Press 's' to capture a single frame.
Press 'f' (or double tap in mobile) to stretch to full screen.
Made with vanilla javascript and GLSL. By @galoandstuff.

metadata.name: Gravity #4
metadata.description:
Gravity is when you can't set/keep your own course and, eventually, crush and break in pieces.

This is an animated piece and it's performance will depend on the power of the machine it is run.
The same configuration is rendered on different color palettes and it's looping endlessly.

The work is built entirely on thi.ng/umbrella libraries and template:

https://github.com/thi-ng/fxhash-tpl

Initial resolution is the screen resolution. Although the piece is supposed to look more or less the same no matter the resolution.

The royalties goes to me (40%), @toxi(30%) and the minter(30%).


Keyboard shortcuts

- space bar : pause/resume animation 
- 2 : download png @ 2 x resolution
- 4 : download png @ 4 x resolution
- x : download canvas as PNG @ current resolution

metadata.name: V.Mountains #180
metadata.description:
V.Mountains is an abstract representation of the turbulence and chaos of our life.



The mountain is a symbol of the way that life is constantly in flux,

of the way that we are constantly trying to make sense of the world around us.



The mountain is a source of inspiration, a place of refuge, a source of strength.

It is a place where we can go to reflect on our lives, to find peace and solace.



The mountain is a symbol of hope.

It is a reminder that, no matter how dark and cold the world may be, there is always a chance for new beginnings.



The mountain is a symbol of the human spirit, and of our ability to persevere in the face of adversity.

It is a representation of our journey through life, with all of its ups and downs.

It is a reminder that, no matter how difficult the path may be,
we can always reach the summit if we are willing to put in the hard work.



Created in Vanilla Javascript.


S - to download image.


Libraries used:

noise.js by Joseph Gentle.
Javascript-Voronoi by Raymond Hill.

metadata.name: Bored Computer Screen #681
metadata.description:
"Bored Computer Screen" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022


Bored Computer Screen (BCS) is a direct descendant of SpecterðŸ‘»pixelâ¬›latteâ˜•, where the central idea is agent and displacement. In BCS, there are agentsâ€”the small moving circlesâ€”that get their colors ripped away by the surrounding pixels. Though they occur on the same screen space, they are separated in their own cells, a simultaneous multiverse of sorts. In some iterations, a very clear voronoi pattern will appear. I didn't consciously strive for this look. It's what naturally happens, when you try to divide space, so that the borders occur exactly in between the closest neighbor. When I first saw this pattern emerge, I wanted to see how far I could get the distinct cells to influence each other. The idea that the same algorithmic processes can happen many times but still separately in a single piece has always interested me (and explored in the Infinite Browse series). BCS is an extension of that, albeit a little more chaotic.

Note:
- Best experience on browsers and devices with support for WebGL2 

Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao) with P5, P5Fbo and perlinjs.

metadata.name: Somewhere In Between #8
metadata.description:
Does entropy across time look the same in a universe different to ours? 

The universe is full of potential energy, recognized as a difference across some scale. Differences in pressure, temperature, state, all act in pursuit of equilibrium. Given enough time, a closed system will eventually fall into an even dispersal. Somewhere in between is some yet-to-be-determined point at which beautiful unexpected forms emerge.

This system takes the standard model of equal exchange and throws it off balance, so each reaction will randomly decide which side has an advantage over the other, and instead of dispersal, one force will win out.

In this system, do similar complex patterns appear? Will we see anything new that doesn't appear with our usual rules?

I found this idea very interesting, that even with no law towards chaos, actually the opposite, we can still end in formlessness. A blank end where no pixel differs from another.

I think that through observation of the world and experimenting with its concepts, we can learn far more about life than just the processes we're studying. 

I'd be very curious to hear about what you take away from the work, and where your somewhere might be <3

Press the space bar to add another step toward chaos
Press â€˜pâ€™ to add 10 steps (enters mode 2)
Press â€˜fâ€™ to enter an animation that will run for 1,056,993,066,125,486,216,810,417,723,659,732,792 years
Press 'f' again to pause
Press â€˜aâ€™ to add a new section of order to the system, you can use this when one state has taken over the canvas

Press â€™sâ€™ to save a png
Press â€˜1â€™ or â€˜2â€™ to begin render between the default 3200x4000px or 6400x8000px

Created by Chris McCully using p5.js, chroma.js, and GLSL.

Built to run best on Chrome and Chromium based browsers.

metadata.name: The Restoration Scheme: Bleaching #60
metadata.description:
â€œBleachingâ€ is the third episode of â€œThe Restoration Schemeâ€ Series. The work was based on Acropora digitifera. 

Corals derive their colors from symbiotic algae. With the change of environment, such as rising water temperature, symbiotic algae leave the coral and therefore it becomes white. Coral bleaching does not mean death, but it does mean that the coral has lost its source of nutrients without symbiotic algae. The coral will be starving to death little by littleÂ if the environment does not improve.

â€”â€”

â€œThe Restoration Schemeâ€ Series
Itâ€™s a virtual action extended from the coral restoration plan led by Delta Electronics Foundation from Taiwan, consisting of five generative corals. Each of them was based on five different species of coral as the theme.
If collectors mint virtual corals, Delta Electronics Foundation will drop coral seedlings collectively in the sea. 

The project is powered by FAB DAO (Formosa Art Bank). The split will donate to the local organization from Taiwan dedicated to the coral restoration scheme.

â€”â€”

About Delta 
Climate change is causing irreversible impacts. Coral reefs, known for their rich biodiversity and the capability to nourish a quarter of marine life, are at the forefront of the crisis. Also known as "tropical rainforests" in the sea, coral reefs have experienced fiveÂ massÂ bleachingÂ events in the past five years. Once global warming exceeds the 2ËšC thresholds, it's likely that 99% of coral reefs will die off worldwide.

In addition to launching a coral restoration initiative along the northeast coast of Taiwan, Delta Electronics Foundation collaborates with Asia University to host "Earth Pulsing: Nurturing Life Exhibition" and releases the first art NFT featuring coral restoration. Through these actions, we hope to evoke public awareness of ecological issues. For more information, please visit https://delta50.deltaww.com/initiative/sea.html

â€”â€”

35 ~ 60 corals to render. You might need some patience for the result.

made with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Plottable Field (8 frames) #275
metadata.description:
'Field' explores the realm of noise field distortions through many different primitives: 15 unique distributions, 16 possible inks, and many kinds of distortions, ink combinations, and animations,...

A SVG file can be exported (right-click save) to plot the 8 frames of this animation on a A4 paper. This is a "plot loop". The physical piece is displayed as aesthetics 4x2 grid of the frames.

You can enjoy the digital version that simulates ink effects. But also, thanks to the utility token decoupling, get a physical one: the digital NFT is the recipe to a plottable art piece, owning it confers the right to plot or request a physical plot from @greweb (https://greweb.me/plots/nft). @greweb would use fountain pens but other plotting artists are free to achieve it with their materials and ship to collectors â€“ as long as NFT is owned at request time.
